PREAMBLE:
	abstract-hdr=SUMMARY,Summary
	refs-hdr=CITED WORKS,Cited works

TITLE:
	Referring to named items under REFERENCES

AUTHOR:
	Eric Johannesson

ABSTRACT:
	Discussing the problem of referring to items in the bibliography,
	with a proposed solution.

Given a named item under REFERENCES, say with the the name ‘ITM\:Euler’,
what should the cross reference ‘[ITM\:Euler]’ look like?
Assuming it is the first item on the list, one could either go for

[]	ITM:alt1
	‘REFERENCES(1)’ (or something similar), or

[]	ITM:alt2
	my preferred solution: ‘[1]’, with item labels under REFERENCES rendered as
	‘[1]’, ‘[2]’, etc.

Having implemented [ITM:alt2], I can refer to [ITM:Euler] and [ITM:Tarski] below, as just indicated.
I think it looks quite nice. For good or bad, it is also familiar from the default in LaTex.

In the future, one would perhaps like to implement som fancier bibliography system compatible with standard bibliography tools (e.g. zotero).
But for now, I think this would suffice.

§ REFS

[]	ITM:Euler
	Euler, Leonhard (1740): De summis serierum reciprocarum. In:
	Commentarii academiae scientiarum Petropolitanae, volume 7,
	pages 123–134

[]	ITM:Tarski
	Tarski, Alfred, and Andrzej Mostowski, and Raphael M.
	Robinson (1953): Undecidable Theories; North-Holland Publishing
	Company; Amsterdam.

